4 SYNOPSIS:
5 Under existing law, the Alabama Commission on
6 Higher Education administers the Alabama Math and
7 Science Teacher Education Program (AMSTEP), which
8 provides a loan repayment award to eligible public K-12
9 math, science, and computer science teachers and an
10 additional loan repayment award to the eligible
11 applicants who are employed in underserved locations in
12 the state.
13 This bill would change the name of the program
14 to the Loan Assistance in Support of Educators in
15 Alabama (LASEA) Program and would expand program
16 eligibility to address additional educator shortages by
17 extending eligibility for loan assistance to educators
18 with certification in acute educator shortage programs
19 and providing additional loan assistance if those
20 educators are employed by public K-12 schools or school
21 systems recognized as acute educator shortage
22 locations.
23 This bill would specify that the Alabama
24 Commission on Higher Education, in consultation with
25 the State Department of Education, would determine
26 which programs, schools, and school systems have acute
27 educator shortages.
28 This bill would also require the commission, in
Page 1

This bill would also require the commission, in
SB74 INTRODUCED
29 consultation with the Alabama Commission on the
30 Evaluation of Services, to develop an accountability
31 and evaluation plan for the program and would provide
32 further for the eligibility of certain applicants who
33 have been continuously employed with a qualifying
34 school.
35
36
37 A BILL
38 TO BE ENTITLED
39 AN ACT
40
41 Relating to the Alabama Math and Science Teacher
42 Education Program (AMSTEP); to change the name of the program
43 to the Loan Assistance in Support of Educators in Alabama
44 (LASEA) Program; to amend Sections 16-5-50, 16-5-51, 16-5-52,
45 16-5-53, 16-5-54, 16-5-54.1, 16-5-55, and 16-5-56, Code of
46 Alabama 1975; to allow educators who complete a program
47 identified as having a shortage of certified educators and who
48 obtain certification in those identified programs to qualify
49 for the loan assistance program; to offer a supplemental
50 payment from the loan assistance program to eligible
51 applicants who are also employed in public K-12 schools or
52 school systems with a shortage of certified educators as
53 determined by the Alabama Commission on Higher Education in
54 consultation with the State Department of Education; to add
55 Sections 16-5-53.1 and 16-5-53.2 to the Code of Alabama 1975,
56 to require the commission, in consultation with the Alabama
Page 2

to require the commission, in consultation with the Alabama
SB74 INTRODUCED
57 Commission on the Evaluation of Services, to develop an
58 accountability and evaluation plan for the program and to
59 provide further for the eligibility of certain applicants who
60 have been continuously employed with a qualifying school; and
61 to repeal Section 16-5-54.2, Code of Alabama 1975, which
62 provides for the reimbursement of individuals who have
63 completed certain alternative certification programs.
64 BE IT ENACTED BY THE LEGISLATURE OF ALABAMA:
65 Section 1. Sections 16-5-50, 16-5-51, 16-5-52, 16-5-53,
66 16-5-54, 16-5-54.1, 16-5-55, and 16-5-56 of the Code of
67 Alabama 1975, are amended to read as follows:
68 "§16-5-50
69 The Alabama Math and Science Teacher Education Program
70 is created pursuant to this article is renamed the Loan
71 Assistance in Support of Educators in Alabama (LASEA)
72 Program."
73 "§16-5-51
74 The purpose of the Alabama Math and Science Teacher
75 Education Program Loan Assistance in Support of Educators in
76 Alabama Program is twofold as follows:
77 (1) To encourage individuals to enroll in and complete
78 educator programs leading to identified as having acute
79 educator shortages and obtain Alabama certification in
80 mathematics, science, or computer science those programs.
81 (2) To improve the educational system in Alabama by
82 encouraging those who complete the program and obtain
83 certification in acute educator shortage programs to accept
84 math, science, or computer science teaching educator positions
Page 3

math, science, or computer science teaching educator positions
SB74 INTRODUCED
85 in Alabama public K-12 schools, preferably in public or school
86 systems, including charter schools, where the shortage of
87 math, science, or computer science teachers, or any
88 combination of the three, is most acute, or in a school that
89 has been designated as a failing school, or any other term
90 adopted to identify an underperforming school, by the State
91 Board of Education or the Legislature that have been
92 identified as acute educator shortage locations."
